    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into pandas DataFrames and keep them in kernel variables for later steps. For each file, compute and return a compact summary (as Python dicts) containing: 1) filename, 2) row_count, 3) min_timestamp, 4) max_timestamp, 5) up to top 20 unique cmdb_id values (sorted), and 6) for metric.csv/trace.csv/log.csv also up to top 20 unique KPI names (kpi_name, trace_name, log_name respectively). For error_logs.csv include up to top 10 unique message samples. Limit printed/displayed results to these compact summaries only. Do not print full tables. Store full DataFrames in kernel variables named df_metric, df_trace, df_log, df_error_logs." }

{
    "analysis": "We have loaded the four telemetry files and obtained compact summaries. metric.csv contains many component-KPI series (including container.node-5 KPIs and typical app.grpc/app.http KPIs) covering the incident window; trace.csv contains many service-to-service trace features; log.csv contains log.error_count and log.row_count for pods; error_logs.csv shows concentrated warnings on frontend pods (sample: \"failed to retrieve ads\"). These summaries suggest frontend pods experienced observable errors and that node-5 container KPIs and adservice/frontend call paths are plausible areas to investigate further. To avoid premature conclusions, the next step is to systematically scan metric time series for anomalies during the incident window using global thresholds computed on full series (P95), so we can rank the most anomalous component-KPI candidates for deeper inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full metric.csv series (no time filtering for threshold calc), for each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group compute the global P95 of 'value'. Then filter metric.csv to the incident time window March 20, 2022 13:00 to 13:30 (inclusive). For each group, count how many points in that window exceed (>=) the group's P95, record the earliest timestamp in-window where this occurs, and the maximum value observed in-window. Return a compact table (limit top 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. Sort the result by anomaly_count_in_window descending, then by max_value_in_window descending. Store the full grouped results in a kernel variable for later steps but only print the top-20 compact table." }

{
    "analysis": "The previous step loaded telemetry and computed per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) P95 thresholds using the full metric series, then counted how many samples in the incident window (2022-03-20 13:00–13:30 UTC+8) exceeded each group's P95. The top results are dominated by static/monotonic KPIs (e.g., StartTime, container_start_time_seconds, system.disk.total), so the P95 threshold equals those constant/monotonic values and every in-window point appears as an 'anomaly'—a threshold artifact rather than a real fault. We therefore need to exclude these static KPIs and re-rank candidates focusing on dynamic KPIs (latency, error rates, app.http/app.grpc counts, container CPU/memory/io, etc.) to find meaningful anomalies during the incident window. The next step is to filter the grouped results to remove obvious static KPIs and present the top dynamic KPI groups by anomaly_count_in_window for further inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the previously stored grouped metric results (the kernel variable containing per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) p95 and in-window anomaly counts), filter out groups whose kpi_name contains any of these substrings (case-sensitive match): 'StartTime', 'start_time_seconds', 'system.disk.total', 'fs_inodes', 'file_descriptors', 'container_fs_inodes', 'runtime.java_lang'. After filtering, return the top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count_in_window descending, then by max_value_in_window descending. Include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. Also return the count of remaining groups after filtering. Limit printed output to this compact table only." }

{
    "analysis": "We filtered out static/monotonic KPIs and found many container memory KPIs on node-5 (and some node-6) that are consistently at or near their P95 during the incident window, indicating persistent high memory usage on containers hosted on node-5. Error logs are concentrated on frontend pods with messages about failing to retrieve ads, which suggests a frontend->adservice call path issue or upstream resource pressure. To narrow the root cause, we must inspect dynamic trace KPIs (latency, error_rate, row_count) to see which services exhibited increased errors/latency or decreased throughput during the window and to correlate those with the memory findings. Trace anomalies (high error_rate or duration, or low row_count) will help identify the downstream faulty service in call chains.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, compute global P95 and P5 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full available series (no time filtering). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window March 20, 2022 13:00 to 13:30 (inclusive). For each group calculate: 1) count_high = number of in-window points with value >= P95, earliest_high_timestamp (if any), and max_value_in_window; 2) count_low = number of in-window points with value <= P5, earliest_low_timestamp (if any), and min_value_in_window. Store the full grouped results in a kernel variable. Return a compact table (top 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95, p5, count_high, earliest_high_timestamp, max_value_in_window, count_low, earliest_low_timestamp, min_value_in_window. Sort by max(count_high, count_low) descending, then by max_value_in_window descending. Limit printed output to this compact table only." }

{
    "analysis": "The trace analysis showed many trace series are constant/zero (P95 = P5 = 0.0), producing artifact anomalies and preventing useful signal extraction. Metric analysis earlier revealed many containers on node-5 exhibiting persistently high memory-related KPIs during the incident window. Error_logs.csv already suggested frontend pods show concentrated warnings such as \"failed to retrieve ads\". To localize the root cause we should now correlate logs (error_logs and aggregated log features) with the metric findings to find the first observed failure timestamp and the most impacted component(s). Specifically, finding which component first reported errors in error_logs and whether log.error_count or reduced log.row_count appears for frontend or adservice will help locate the root cause and occurrence time before drilling deeper with targeted metric/traces.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From error_logs.csv, filter rows within the incident window March 20, 2022 13:00 to 13:30 (inclusive). Group by cmdb_id and compute: count_of_messages, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp. For each cmdb_id return up to 5 distinct sample messages. Return a compact table sorted by count_of_messages descending (limit top 20). Also return the overall earliest error_logs timestamp across all components in the window. Store the filtered error_logs DataFrame in a kernel variable for later steps. Print only the compact aggregate results." }

{
    "analysis": "We have identified that error logs are concentrated on frontend-0/1/2 with earliest messages at ~2022-03-20 13:00:00–13:00:01 (UTC+8) reporting \"failed to retrieve ads\". Metric analysis so far shows many containers on node-5 (and some on node-6) with persistently high memory KPIs (container_memory_rss, container_memory_cache, container_memory_mapped_file, etc.) throughout the incident window; these memory KPIs equal or are very close to their P95, making them strong candidates for resource-pressure faults. Trace metrics were mostly zero/constant and not informative. We still need to confirm (1) which frontend/adservice pods are hosted on node-5, (2) whether node-5 shows node-level memory pressure (and/or CPU/disk issues), and (3) the exact first timestamp where a meaningful memory anomaly appears for the implicated pods or node. These confirmations will help localize the root cause component and occurrence time before deciding the root cause reason (e.g., node memory consumption causing service failures).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full metric.csv (df_metric) compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) for the following components: frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, adservice-0, adservice-1, adservice-2, and node-5. Identify memory-related KPIs as those whose kpi_name contains the substring 'memory' or 'container.node-5'. After computing P95 from the full series, filter metric data to the incident window March 20, 2022 13:00 to 13:30 (inclusive) and for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, anomaly_count_in_window (value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first in-window timestamp with value >= p95, or null), and max_value_in_window. Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by cmdb_id then anomaly_count_in_window desc. Also return the total number of distinct memory-related (cmdb_id,kpi_name) groups found for these components. Store the full grouped results in a kernel variable for later steps." }

{
    "analysis": "We have: (1) loaded all telemetry and computed global P95 thresholds per component-KPI; (2) found frontend-0/1/2 produce concentrated error logs starting at ~2022-03-20 13:00:00 (UTC+8) with messages \"failed to retrieve ads\"; (3) metric analysis shows many container memory KPIs tied to 'container.node-5' (and some 'container.node-6') with values equal to their P95 across the incident window—suggesting persistent high memory usage on containers hosted on node-5 rather than isolated spikes; (4) traces are mostly zero/constant and not informative. From these results we need to verify pod placement (which pods run on node-5) to see if the affected frontends/adservice pods are hosted on node-5, and inspect node-5 host-level memory KPIs for meaningful deviations in the incident window. This will help determine whether node-5 memory pressure temporally aligns with the first frontend errors (around 13:00) and thus localize the root cause component (node or pod) and occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) From the full metric dataset, find all distinct cmdb_id values that have any kpi_name containing the substring 'container.node-5'. Return: count_of_unique_cmdb_ids and up to the top 20 sorted cmdb_id names (sorted alphabetically). Also explicitly indicate whether frontend-0, frontend-1, or frontend-2 are present in that list (yes/no).\n\n2) For cmdb_id == 'node-5' in metric.csv, identify all kpi_name values that contain 'memory' (case-insensitive match) or 'mem'. For each such kpi_name compute the global P95 using the full series, then filter to the incident window (2022-03-20 13:00 to 13:30 inclusive) and report: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, anomaly_count_in_window (value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first in-window timestamp with value >= p95 or null), max_value_in_window. Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count_in_window desc then max_value_in_window desc. Store results in kernel variables for later steps. Print only these compact aggregates." }

{
    "analysis": "We have loaded and summarized all telemetry. Metric analysis (global P95 on full series) flagged many static/monotonic KPIs as artifacts. After filtering those, a strong signal is persistent, high container memory metrics tied to container.node-5 across many service pods; frontend-0/1/2 are present among components reporting node-5 container KPIs. Error_logs show frontend pods emitting many warnings starting at ~2022-03-20 13:00:00 UTC+8 with message \"failed to retrieve ads\". Node-5 host memory KPIs show small, real increases around 13:13, but frontend errors begin at ~13:00 — so the temporal correlation between node memory spikes and frontend errors is not yet conclusive. Traces were mostly zero/constant and not helpful. To localize root cause we must correlate logs and dynamic metrics: specifically check whether aggregated log features (log.error_count and log.row_count) for frontend and adservice pods show anomalies at ~13:00 (error_count increase or row_count drop) using global thresholds computed on full series. This will help confirm which component first exhibited a measurable fault and whether the fault is at the pod (frontend/adservice) level or node-level resource pressure.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv, restrict analysis to cmdb_id in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, adservice-0, adservice-1, adservice-2]. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) group compute global P95 and P5 using the full series (no time filtering). Then filter rows to the incident window March 20, 2022 13:00 to 13:30 inclusive. For each group report: cmdb_id, log_name, p95, p5, count_above_p95_in_window (value >= p95), earliest_above_p95_timestamp (first in-window timestamp with value >= p95 or null), max_value_in_window, count_below_p5_in_window (value <= p5), earliest_below_p5_timestamp (first in-window timestamp with value <= p5 or null), min_value_in_window. Also return the overall earliest in-window timestamp among all above-P95 or below-P5 events for these groups (or null if none). Store the full grouped results in a kernel variable for later steps and print only the compact table (limit to top 20 rows sorted by max(count_above_p95_in_window, count_below_p5_in_window) desc)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have correlated multiple signals: (1) error_logs show frontend-0/1/2 emitted many warnings starting at ~2022-03-20 13:00:00 UTC+8 with the repeated message \"failed to retrieve ads\"; (2) aggregated log.error_count metrics for frontend pods show elevated counts later in the window (first above-P95 events around 13:09–13:13), suggesting raw warnings began earlier than aggregated error_count spikes; (3) many containers running on node-5 (including frontend and adservice pods) show high, near-constant memory KPIs (container_memory_* tied to container.node-5), but node-5 host memory P95 anomalies (pct_usage/used) show only small increases around 13:13, which is later than the earliest frontend warnings (~13:00); (4) adservice log.error_count series are zero (artifact) while some adservice log.row_count shows minor deviations near 13:09–13:10. Traces have been largely zero/constant and not informative. From these facts, the earliest observable symptom is frontend warnings at 13:00:00. To decide the root cause we need the exact raw error log contents and timestamps for the first frontend messages (to see if they indicate timeouts, connection refused, or upstream errors) and to check if any upstream service (adservice) shows errors at the same time. The next step is to inspect the raw earliest error_log entries in the incident window to get precise messages and timestamps.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the stored df_error_logs_window (error_logs filtered to the incident window), return the earliest 20 rows sorted by timestamp with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, message. Also provide, for each of frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, the first 5 error log messages (timestamp and message). Limit output to these compact results only." }

{
    "analysis": "We inspected raw error logs and aggregated metrics/traces. Findings so far: (1) error_logs show all three frontend pods repeatedly logged \"failed to retrieve ads\" starting at 2022-03-20 13:00:00 (UTC+8) — the earliest observable symptom; (2) aggregated frontend log.error_count shows elevated counts later (first aggregated spikes ~13:09–13:13), indicating persistent warnings started earlier than aggregated metric spikes; (3) many containers on node-5 (including frontend and adservice pods) show high/near-constant container memory KPIs, but host node-5 memory pct/used only shows small increases around 13:13 — later than the initial frontend warnings; (4) adservice aggregated log.error_count series are zero (artifact) while some adservice log.row_count and trace series have small deviations around ~13:09–13:10. Traces overall were sparse/mostly zero, making it inconclusive so far whether adservice or network errors caused frontend failures. Given the earliest symptom is frontend warnings at 13:00:00, we must now look for any non-zero (or otherwise meaningful) trace signals on the frontend->adservice call path that temporally align with the first frontend warnings to determine whether the root cause is an upstream service (adservice), pod/container resource (frontend or adservice), or network. The next actionable step is to scan trace groups related to 'from_frontend' (frontend-originated traces to adservice or other services) and select only trace groups that have non-zero/full-series p95>0 or max>0, then report in-window anomaly counts and earliest anomaly timestamps so we can see if traces indicate failures at ~13:00.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, select groups where trace_name contains the substring 'from_frontend' (case-sensitive). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global P95 and P5 and the full-series max and min using the entire trace.csv (no time filtering). Then filter to groups where either full-series p95 > 0 or full-series max > 0 (non-zero series). For those groups, filter rows to the incident window March 20, 2022 13:00 to 13:30 inclusive and compute: count_above_p95_in_window (value >= p95), earliest_above_p95_timestamp (first in-window timestamp with value >= p95 or null), max_value_in_window, count_below_p5_in_window (value <= p5), earliest_below_p5_timestamp (first in-window timestamp with value <= p5 or null), min_value_in_window. Return a compact table (limit top 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95, p5, full_series_max, count_above_p95_in_window, earliest_above_p95_timestamp, max_value_in_window, count_below_p5_in_window, earliest_below_p5_timestamp, min_value_in_window. Sort by max(count_above_p95_in_window, count_below_p5_in_window) descending, then by full_series_max descending. Store the full grouped results in a kernel variable for later steps. Print only the compact table." }

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through preprocessing, metric anomaly scanning, trace inspection, and log correlation. Key facts established so far: (1) All three frontend pods emitted repeated warning messages \"failed to retrieve ads\" starting at 2022-03-20 13:00:00 UTC+8 — this is the earliest observable symptom. (2) Aggregated frontend log.error_count shows elevated counts later (~13:09–13:13), but raw error logs begin at 13:00:00. (3) Many container memory KPIs tied to container.node-5 are persistently high or constant, but node-5 host memory shows only small increases around 13:13 — later than the initial frontend warnings, so node-level memory pressure is not clearly the initial trigger. (4) Traces are mostly sparse/near-zero, though some from_frontend trace groups show small non-zero values and row_count deviations at 13:00, consistent with frontend errors. (5) adservice aggregated error_count series are zeros (artifact), and adservice traces show only very small values; there is no clear adservice failure signal at exactly 13:00 from aggregated metrics. Given the earliest symptom is frontend warnings at 13:00:00 and node memory spikes occur later, possible root causes include upstream service unavailability (e.g., adservice), network issues (packet loss/latency) affecting frontend->adservice calls, or frontend-side failures. To decide, we need to look for metric indicators of process termination/restarts, OOM events, or network errors. The next atomic step is to scan metric KPI names for terms indicative of restarts/ooms/process termination or network errors (e.g., restart, oom, kill, exit, retransmit, packet, loss, tcp, latency, throttled) and return compact counts and whether they appear during the incident window. This will tell us whether a container or node had a termination or a network metric spiked at or before 13:00:00.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Scan metric.csv kpi_name values and find distinct kpi_names that contain any of these substrings (case-insensitive): 'restart', 'oom', 'kill', 'exit', 'crash', 'process', 'terminated', 'tcp', 'retransmit', 'retrans', 'packet', 'loss', 'latency', 'throttled', 'error'. For each matching kpi_name return: kpi_name, total_row_count_in_full_series, up to 10 example cmdb_id values (sorted), and count_of_rows_within_incident_window (2022-03-20 13:00 to 13:30 inclusive). Limit output to top 20 kpi_names sorted by total_row_count_in_full_series descending. Store the full set of matching rows in a kernel variable for later inspection and print only the compact table." }

{
    "analysis": "The KPI scan found a strong concentration of network- and error-related metrics tied to container.node-5 (container network receive/transmit packets/errors) plus CPU throttling metrics on node-5, and node-level TCP/UDP error counters (system.tcp.retrans_pct, system.net.udp.*). These signals are present in the incident window and are plausible causes for frontend failures that report \"failed to retrieve ads\". However, we have not yet confirmed temporal alignment: frontend warnings start at ~2022-03-20 13:00:00 UTC+8 while earlier node-5 host memory spikes occurred slightly later (~13:13). The network/error KPIs on node-5 are promising candidates but need time-correlation with the earliest frontend errors. We should therefore compute global thresholds (P95) for node-5 network- and TCP/UDP-related KPIs using the full series, then check in-window how many points exceed those thresholds and, crucially, the earliest in-window timestamp where a threshold breach occurs. This will tell us whether node-5 network problems (retransmits/packet errors/throttling) began at or before 13:00:00 and could be the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Focus on node-5 network and related KPIs. From the metric dataset, select groups where cmdb_id == 'node-5' OR kpi_name contains 'container.node-5' (to include container-scoped node-5 metrics) and where kpi_name (case-insensitive) contains any of these substrings: 'network', 'transmit', 'receive', 'error', 'err', 'retrans', 'tcp', 'udp', 'throttled'. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) group compute the global P95 using the full series (no time filtering). Then filter the group's data to the incident window March 20, 2022 13:00 to 13:30 inclusive and calculate: anomaly_count_in_window (value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first in-window timestamp with value >= p95 or null), and max_value_in_window. Return a compact table (limit top 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. Sort the results by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending (nulls last), then anomaly_count_in_window descending. Also return the overall earliest_anomaly_timestamp across all returned groups (or null if none). Store the full grouped results in a kernel variable for later steps." }

